Hi, my name is Joe and I am offering virtual math tutoring in Berkeley and beyond!

Can't finish your homework? Stressed about a test coming up? Confused in lecture? I can fix that.

I have been tutoring math for 4 years now starting as an on-campus tutor at the UC Berkeley Student Learning Center where I honed my craft tutoring college math courses. I now have my B.A. in mathematics from UC Berkeley and am pursuing my masters also in mathematics at NYU.

I have a passion for math education and a vested belief that no one is simply 'bad at math', rather, we are all like a block of marble before it is sculpted into a masterpiece, simply waiting to unlock our true math potential. My method focuses on taking seemingly inaccessible concepts and algorithms breaking them down with real-life analogies, examples, and frameworks to make them more digestible. A mathematical divide and conquer strategy.

A typical lesson will take place on Zoom with a virtual whiteboard where we will work through whatever topics or problems are giving you problems that week. I often prepare some sort of instructive lesson (I like to tell explanatory math stories) and I follow along with your course syllabus to prepare practice problems and motivate/anticipate upcoming topics.

I offer weekly and one-off private sessions at $80/hour. My goal is to meet your needs whatever they may be so if you need any special accommodation please feel free to ask!

Courses:

SAT, GRE, Pre-Algebra, Algebra, Geometry, Pre-Calculus, Trigonometry, Calculus

Multivariable Calculus, Linear Algebra, Real Analysis, Abstract Algebra, Complex Analysis, and more!!!

Please email me for resume and inquiries. I look forward to hearing from you!

Math, physics, and chemistry are too often taught to be complicated, but that's antithetical. Math and science are meant to take our complex world and make it simple. I believe in breaking down problems so each step is as simple as possible. As I often tell my students: small steps, not big leaps. I am a native San Franciscan and and a graduate of University High School. I am capable of tutoring calculus through middle school math as well as high school and intro college physics and high school chemistry. Hi, my name is Alexander Blake, and I have been tutoring for over 10,000 hours! I graduated with a Bachelor's in Computer Science from California State University, Fullerton. In my time tutoring, I have tutored elementary through graduate level students.
I have successfully prepared students for SAT and ACT Math tests, and up to Calculus level work. In high school, I was in an accelerated math program where I was able to take AP Calculus AB my junior year, and AP Calculus BC my senior year. After taking the AP Calculus AB & BC Exams, I scored a 5 out of 5 on both tests. This allowed me to not only begin my higher-level math courses early in college but has also enabled me to keep my math skills refined, and graduate with a 3.8 GPA.
My tutoring philosophy focuses on the individual. I like to know what each of my clients likes to do outside of school so I can relate the math concepts they are learning about things they enjoy doing. To accomplish this, I personally design my lesson plans and customize them to my client's personality. For example, if I have a student that plays basketball, I will have them solve problems that incorporate concepts of basketball, such as finding a team's field goal percentage. By focusing on each person uniquely, I am able to fully understand why the student is not grasping certain concepts and can help them understand concepts and terms they are already familiar with. This is why all of my students have been and will continue to be successful!

While I am able to teach every topic on the exam, from SDS-PAGE to Newtonian mechanics, my teaching style focuses on strategically approaching and dissecting the passage material.  The AAMC test writers assume you have the prerequisite information internalized and are testing you on puzzles that they build upon that information.  Any student that wants to excel on the MCAT must not only learn the base material but must also understand how those puzzles work.  There are patterns to how the AAMC generates their puzzles and those patterns can be taught and learned.  Since I have been teaching the exam for 5 years now, I've worked through hundreds and hundreds of practice passages.  I use my experience to help students learn how to read and interpret the questions in the manner that an MCAT writer would.


In addition to the nuts and bolts of how to work through the exam, I also work with the majority of my students on creating a schedule from day 1 through test day.  This covers not only what materials to tackle and when, but when to take full lengths, when to correct them, when to review, and when to rest.  I've seen pretty much all the material from every major company that students use to study for this exam and I know how to place all of it on a timeline that benefits the student the most.

Bay Area High School Math Enrichment Program offered online by UC Berkeley PhD student. Topics covered: Complex Analysis and Abstract Algebra. Apply by January 21, 2022. Find out more about this learning opportunity below.


My name is Kabir Kapoor and I am an NSF Fellow and mathematics Ph.D. student at UC Berkeley, currently on medical leave. I am running a math enrichment program for advanced high school students in the Bay Area, starting late-January and ending early-June (exact dates TBA). 

For advanced high school students, there are plenty of good resources to prepare for math competitions, but few good resources to learn college-level math. Typically, high school students with an interest in learning advanced mathematics must attend courses at nearby colleges. These courses are large, impersonal, and not always taught from a pure-math perspective. My enrichment program seeks to fill this niche. 

Format

I will run two courses over Zoom/Google Meet. The first will cover complex analysis and the second will cover abstract algebra, both taught at a level accessible to advanced high school students. For each course, I will give 2 hours of lecture per week, assign biweekly homeworks, and hold 1 hour of office-hours per week. I am taking no more than 9 students per course, and no more than 15 students total. This is so that the students can receive my full attention and easily collaborate with each other. The lecture and office-hour times will be set to fit the schedules of the students.

Course Content and Prerequisites

The universal prerequisite is an interest in learning mathematics. Competition experience can be helpful, but is not necessary. Both courses will be proof based, some familiarity with writing proofs is beneficial, though learning proof-writing can be viewed as a part of the program. 

Complex Analysis

For an idea of the course content, please see Tristan Needham’s Visual Complex Analysis. A more advanced text, which will be incorporated as appropriate, is Stein and Shakarchi’s Complex Analysis. The only formal prerequisite is a facility with calculus, at least at the level of an AP Calculus BC course. 

Abstract Algebra

For an idea of the course content, please see Charles C. Pinter’s A Book of Abstract Algebra. A more advanced text, which will be incorporated as appropriate, is Abstract Algebra by David S. Dummit and Richard M. Foote. The only formal prerequisite is a facility with precalculus. 

Pricing

The students can sign up for either 1 or 2 classes without affecting the price, which will be fixed at $80 a week. If a student signs up for both courses, the price comes out to $13.33 an hour. 

Teaching Qualifications

I have taught, mentored, and tutored college and high school math students consistently for the past 7 years. At Cornell, I facilitated these activities as the president of the undergraduate math club and a tutor at the Math Support Center. At Berkeley, I guided an undergraduate in an independent reading project through the Directed Reading Program. I have also privately tutored.

Academic Qualifications

1.	Have coauthored 3 math publications 
2.	Awarded NSF Graduate Research Fellowship for Ph.D. studies at UC Berkeley
3.	Graduated summa cum laude, Merrill Presidential Scholar (top 1% of all graduating students in class of 2020), and Phi Beta Kappa (junior year) at Cornell University
4.	Awarded 2019 Goldwater Scholarship

Applications

I will be accepting applications and questions via email until January 21, 2022. To apply, write to me with a brief (at most 1 page) description of yourself, including your mathematical interests and background. Please indicate which of the two courses you are applying to. I prefer to take students who are eager to collaborate with other students.

I work with students online. I will offer classes online, where students can connect from different locations, and they may share the burden of my default rate. The default rate becomes $40 + $10 for each additional student. E.g., 4 students would each pay 1/4 of $40 plus $30. I practice patience and a perfectly positive attitude toward my students, striving to not judge others.
In sessions, concepts are explained clearly if there is a need. Otherwise, practice is the focus. Active learning is best in any subject. Teaching strategy in test taking is beneficial to many students. Teaching error-free programming techniques is valuable in CS.
I want to help students learn problematic material. Beating the fear of success is possible through sustained small successes. The only real teaching/tutoring goal is to teach a student everything the teacher/tutor knows so that the teacher/tutor is no longer necessary.
Learning technical subjects requires problem solving, and learning programming languages requires specifically programming practice. Reading programs, if done carefully, is helpful, but there is no substitute for programming.  Just like in mathematics and physics, one must read and actively practice (program) to master the subject. With sufficient programming practice, there is no need to do rote memorization of code idioms -- such things will come automatically. Programming is problem solving, and it is more similar to problem solving in math than in physics, I think. Learning programming is ideally like learning to play a musical instrument. Learning math and physics also require significant practice to by-pass rote memorization, develop speed in problem solving, and develop intuition.
Getting code from the internet is not a preferred approach to programming. It is dangerous to your academic career, and it is not helpful in the long run if it is not significantly modified and understood. I rarely use code from the internet, and I almost always write completely original code to solve a problem. Any code developed jointly during a session should be completely assimilated by the student. It is essential to be able to easily read code in the language at hand.
Note that High School physics teachers with a B.Ed. have the weakest background in physics courses. A High School teacher with a B.S. in physics is much better prepared to teach physics. An M.Ed. high school teacher does not take as many physics courses as a M.S. physics teacher, and could still know less physics than a B.S. in physics teacher. A Ph.D. in education teacher is similar to a M.Ed. in physics teacher in terms of physics courses, unless an M.S in physics was earned. A Ph.D. in physics has the most experience in physics courses, and a Ph.D. in theoretical physics is could be even better prepared. Postdocs also add to a Ph.D.'s preparedness to teach.

Accelerated Algebra: In this course, the concepts behind Algebra 1 and Algebra 2 are combined with a focus on precalculus to challenge students and prepare them for the next level of math. Accelerated Precalculus/Calculus: This course is intended for students who have taken or are planning to take precalculus/calculus and want to learn at a faster, more challenging level. This is ideal for students planning to take the AP Calculus AB/BC Exams or College Math.

Calculus for Young Learners:  is a special course intended for children who aspire to gain a deep understanding of the concepts unique to Calculus - limits, differentiation, and integration. Algebra is the most vital subject in mathematics, and the biggest hurdle for many students. It requires mathematicians to recall and combine all fundamental skills, while constantly introducing abstract concepts. Any gaps or weaknesses in algebra are critical obstacles.

Teaching Philosophy
My job is to help students achieve lifelong success as mathematicians. Dialogue and immersion lie at the heart of my teaching philosophy. Through constant dialogue, your student will learn how to SPEAK math, and understand it when spoken. An articulate math student will easily comprehend lectures, ask pertinent questions, and generally stay ahead of the class. By immersing in private lessons, students gain the momentum necessary to excel. Group lessons engage students in a social structure which rewards their interest and skill in math.

Individual Lessons
One-on-one lessons focus on improving fundamental (prealgebra) skills, and covering algebra topics that students may have missed in class. I have my own materials and methods, refined through use, and individual lessons can be catered to each student based on their school's exact curriculum. Group Lessons ($25/1hr)
Research shows that consistent, intimate group study with close guidance yields massive results. Working in pairs and teams, your student will discuss concepts, solve problems, and explain their understanding to the group. Developing social skills while navigating difficult concepts builds profound confidence, and naturally sparks interest in math.

Education:

* Studied abroad in 2007 in South Africa, attended University of Kwa-Zulu Natal.

* Graduated from Arcadia University in 2012 with a Masters degree in Special Education. 

Teaching Experience: 
For the last 12 years, I have provided special education services within the School District of Philadelphia. The first two years of my teaching career were spent at West Philadelphia High School. In 2011, I decided to switch schools and became a special education teacher at an elementary school in Northeast Philadelphia. After 6 years of proving myself and gaining experience, I then transitioned into the role of Special Education Liaison (the head of the special education department). I have held that role since 2017. Lastly, I have been providing tutoring services for the past 5 years. 

Plan of Action:
Given you are interested in having your child make gains in Reading or Math, my plan would be as follows: 

1.	In the first session, I would have your child complete a diagnostic assessment which would allow me to gauge the child’s current educational levels and know which areas need development. 

2.	The sessions that follow will be based on the skill(s) that need to be developed. As an example, if a child needs help in sounding out multi-syllabic words (decoding), I would conduct a research-based reading program that would help generate awareness of certain sounds of letters, and common letter combinations. The key would be repetition for each lesson.  An assessment (with results provided) will be given to the child after a number of lessons to see if they have retained the information that was taught. 

3.	After each assessment, a debriefing session with the parent is pivotal. This would allow you to see how your child is progressing, know which skills have been worked on, and which skills still need fine tuning. 

In short, my method for approaching any tutoring opportunity is diagnose, teach, assess and reteach as needed.
